# ES6 Classes

Classes are primary builders in Modern JS. They provide a much cleaner syntax for creating objects and handling inheritance compared to prototypes.

---

## 1. Class Declaration

A class is a blueprint for creating objects.

```javascript
class User {
  constructor(name, email) {
    this.name = name;
    this.email = email;
  }

  // Method
  sayHello() {
    return `Hi, I am ${this.name}`;
  }
}

const john = new User('John', 'john@test.com');
```

## 2. Getters and Setters

Allow you to define properties that act like methods but are accessed like variables. Perfect for validation!

```javascript
class Account {
  constructor(balance) {
    this._balance = balance; // '_' naming convention for private
  }

  get balance() {
    return `$${this._balance}`;
  }

  set balance(amount) {
    if (amount < 0) return;
    this._balance = amount;
  }
}
```

## 3. Static Methods

Methods called on the class itself, not on instances. Useful for utility functions.

```javascript
class MathUtil {
  static add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
  }
}
console.log(MathUtil.add(5, 10)); // 15
```

